  "opinion": "As a 20-year-old hairdresser living in Rome, I see fake content on social media as a real headache, but I don't let it get to me—I've got good mental health and a busy life with my two kids, painting, and gardening. I'm not on social media much, just a few times a week, so when I do scroll, I keep it simple and friendly. With my high extraversion and agreeableness, I love connecting with people, but I've learned to trust my gut. If something seems too wild or doesn't match what I know from my Hindu beliefs or everyday chats in the salon, I just ignore it or ask a friend. I'm not big on deep thinking—my openness is low—so I don't dig into every post; I focus on real stuff like my family and hobbies. Since I'm retired early, maybe from a family business, I value honesty in my work and life, so fake news feels like a bad haircut—it's just wrong. To deal with it, I stick to reliable sources I know, like local news or friends I trust, and I avoid sharing anything iffy. My low conscientiousness means I'm not super organized, but that's okay—I keep it casual and move on quickly. In Rome, where gossip spreads fast, I've seen how fake content can mess things up, so I try to be a positive voice, sharing real moments from my painting or garden instead. Overall, I think the best way to handle fake content is to stay grounded, trust your circle, and not let it ruin your day—life's too short for that nonsense!",
